node.text: Sopes are rounds of griddled masa with a little rim around the edge to hold delicious fillings. “In my house, sopes were always filled with refried black beans, pulled chicken, chopped romaine lettuce, crema, crumbled fresh cheese, and then one or two salsas and guacamole or avocado to top,” writes Epi contributor @Fanygerson. But sopes are made to be customized, she says. Learn the cooking method in the video above, and check out the link in our bio to get the recipe.

node.text: Gorditas are one of the most popular street foods in Mexico. According to @fanygerson, the translation means “little fatties,” and they’re thick masa pockets that are toasted on a comal, then stuffed with fillings. Watch the video to learn all of Gerson’s tips and tricks, then click the link in our bio for the recipe—and a sweet variation, too.

node.text: You can find tlacoyos all across Mexico—and they’re one of @fanygerson’s favorite street food snacks. The thick oval-shaped masa patties are crispy on the outside, stuffed with beans or other fillings, and piled high with a refreshing cactus salad. Here, Fany shows you how to make them, step by step, to devour right away or stock your freezer. Read more and get the recipe at the link in our bio.

node.text: “For many families, making tamales is a ritual, and younger and older generations each have specific roles in the process,” writes Epi contributor, chef @fanygerson. Here, Gerson walks you through the whole method, step by step, so you can make the fluffiest, most flavorful tamales of your life. Read more and get the recipe at the link in our bio.

node.text: When chef and cookbook author Fany Gerson (@fanygerson) first moved to New York from Mexico over 20 years ago, it wasn’t a matter of *wanting* to find good tortillas—she *needed* them. Mass-produced tortillas from supermarkets and delis had nothing in common with the supple, fragrant fresh tortillas she knew and loved in Mexico. So she started making her own—now she’s here to share her tips, step by step. Read more and get the recipe at the link in our bio. Director: @c.emanuelsmith DP: @bendewster Editor: @elliottjchrist

node.text: One day, you will be in a market, and you will pass the coconuts. They will grab your attention. You'll say to yourself, "I'm going to buy this coconut." You settle at the register, and bring your groceries home. You put most of them away. As you hold up that last item, you will ask yourself: "Why did I buy this coconut?" At least we can help answer how to open it!

node.title: 50 People Try to Crack Open a Coconut

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by epicurious on August 09, 2021. May be an image of food.

node.text: Grilled fish is simple, delicious, and just right for hot weather. For meaty steaks of swordfish, albacore, and halibut, all you need is a kiss of high heat from a grill and a simple vinaigrette. This halibut is paired with a simple salad of tomatoes, hearts of palm, basil, and a splash of lemon juice. Tap the link in bio for a collection that has all the tips you need to grill fish with confidence. Photo @yungbludlau

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by epicurious on August 08, 2021. May be an image of dessert.

node.text: If you love to customize, this Any Way Ice Cream Icebox Cake will be be your go-to summer dessert. With a few tweaks to the standard icebox cake formula, this variation becomes a standout snack on a hot day. In this recipe, peach jam is folded into whipped cream for a fruity element, Ritz crackers add a salty and buttery base, and a layer of butter pecan ice cream right through the middle rounds it out. But there are endless directions you can take this dessert in, so check out the link in bio for recipes and tips. Photo @j_deleo, Food Styling @gatton_michelle

Keep those drinks ice cold! Epi tested top-rated hard coolers to see which models kept our ice frozen and our beers chilled the longest. Whether you need one for backyard barbecues and pool parties, or one that's hearty enough for road trips and camping, we’ve got some fantastic options in a range of prices. Find the right cooler for your budget and lifestyle at the link in bio. Photo @travis.rainey

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by epicurious on August 06, 2021. May be an image of 1 person and pizza.

node.text: Haul out the blender and fire up the grill. In Epi’s new Take It Outside guide, there’s plenty of inspiration to keep your menus fun and your outdoor space feeling fresh. Grilled pizzas, no-cook meals, and easy make-ahead picnic recipes await, along with fantastic lanterns, pitchers, and plates to spruce up your dinner table. Head over to the link in bio for the whole guide. Photo and Food Styling @j_deleo

node.text: The publishing world has long ignored Black pitmasters, and many barbecue books in the past glossed over or excluded Black contributions. These new books from @soulfoodscholar and @pitmasterrodneyscott do better. “Come for the recipes but stay for the stories of barbecue’s past, present, and future,” says Epi Contributor Vonnie Williams (@sincerelyvonnie), who particularly loved Scott’s brilliant macaroni and cheese. Find out more—and pick up a copy of each book—at the link in bio. Photo @j_deleo

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by epicurious on August 05, 2021. May be an image of food and indoor.

node.text: “This salad is exactly the type of dish I enjoy serving for lunch outdoors or at the park,” says @hettymckinnon. Her latest recipe for Epi makes egg salad the creamy canvas for grilled veggies. Add charred broccoli and as much herby goodness as you like, then top with chili crisp for some heat and crunch. Serve with crusty bread to mop up the deliciously spicy, eggy mess at the bottom of the plate. Get the recipe for this picnic-perfect salad at the link in bio. Photo @j_deleo, Food Styling @curlygirlcooks

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by epicurious on August 05, 2021. May be an image of fig and dessert.

node.text: Figs are endlessly versatile, adding sweetness to savory dishes and taking the spotlight in desserts. Caramelize some halved figs and top them with bacon for a sweet and salty one-bite appetizer. Wrap them in puff pastry and you’ve got Figs-in-a-Blanket. Add them to cupcakes or even your morning yogurt—simply because they taste so good. If fresh figs have started showing up at your local market, grab a basket and make the most of this delicately delicious fruit while it’s ripe. Oh, and get all the fig recipes you need at the link in bio. Photo @yungbludlau

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by epicurious on August 04, 2021. May be an image of dessert.

node.text: If you’ve been craving a throwback to your favorite lunchbox cookies, look no further. Samah Dada (@dadaeats) has blessed us with these peanut butter coconut cream cookie sandwiches, which are sure to become a favorite in your baking routine. (And guess what? They're totally vegan.) Make a batch for your next picnic or cookout, and check out the link in bio to get cooking. Photo @j_deleo, Food Styling @c_barsch

node.text: Meet the best cookbooks of summer 2021. This collection from Epi's Lauren Joseph will help you make the most of peak produce season—and also become regulars in your kitchen year-round. If you like no-fuss dining, farm-to-table eating, and lighthearted cocktails, head over to the link in bio to explore these fantastic titles. Photo @travis.rainey

node.text: Pistachio ice cream + raspberry jam + whipped cream + Biscoff cookies = a delicious and colorful ice cream icebox cake. This variation on a classic recipe delivers a sweet-nutty-spiced slice that’s as flavorful as it is pretty on the plate. It's perfect for sharing with others and it comes together in a matter of minutes. Just head over to the link in bio for the recipe and tips. Photo @j_deleo, Food Styling @gatton_michelle

Artisan salt is sea salt, but not all sea salt is artisan. Do you know the difference? Epi has a new guide from Janet Rausa Fuller and Joe Sevier (@PithZester) that breaks down 9 common types of salt, with a handy guide to swapping one kind for another. (Trust us, you’ll wanna save the chart to your phone.) Check out the link in bio to find out more about using these varieties of salt in your cooking. Photo @travis.rainey

node.text: “Even though I have a full collection of high-end knives, I often reach for my Dexter cleaver to do a task that might otherwise require two or three separate tools,” says Hsiao-Ching Chou (@mychinesesoulfood), whose mother taught her the value of a good bone-cracking, garlic-thwacking, fish-filleting, vegetable-dicing cleaver at their family's Chinese restaurant. A well-made cleaver will last a lifetime and might just become your go-to knife. Buy one for yourself now at the link in bio. Photo and Prop Styling @j_deleo
